Thank you to those of you who have supported the efforts of Hope of Guinea, former Peace Corps Volunteers,  and MindLeaps by donating to our previous fundraising page. We were able to raise $2, 755 because of you!In thinking about our mission of giving hope to all children, we decided to have a round 2 for our fundraising campaign. More and more people are learning about this initiative and find it a worthwhile investment. If you go to Hope of Guinea's Facebook page (https://www.facebook.com/hope.ofguinea/), you can get more information about the Camp, our partners and volunteers. With your support we can give students in Guinea the opportunity to discover hands on experiments, and the tools and confidence to see themselves as leaders and innovators within the STEAM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts, and Math) fields and within their communities. Background- GuineaGuinea is one of the least developed countries in the world, rated 182nd in the Human Development Index and recently ravaged by an Ebola epidemic. From these facts alone, it is no surprise that the educational system in Guinea is not able to provide all students the necessary tools to be critical learners, innovators and leaders. Guinea desperately needs health care providers, infrastructure engineers, well-trained teachers, and many more well educated professionals. However, relatively few development organizations are on the ground in Guinea, compared to nearby Sierra Leone, Liberia, and Senegal. Cultural barriers are high, especially for English-speaking and Christian charities in this Francophone, primarily Muslim country. And yet, curious, determined young Guineans are just begging for the chance to learn more and expand their horizons. This is where you, Hope of Guinea and its partners come in. InitiativeThe Hope of Guinea STEAM ( Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts and Science) Camp 2016 that will take place from July 11th to July 29th. It is a joint partnership between Hope of Guinea, MindLeaps, and Returned Peace Corps Volunteers from Guinea. The STEAM Camp is based on a successful project designed and implemented by Peace Corps Volunteers in the summer of 2014. Well into implementation, the concept of the camp is to provide resources and ways of learning to kids in Guinea whether in  school or on the street. Hope of Guinea aims to provide hope to all children with its first STEAM Camp. For three weeks, from Monday through Thursday, selected kids of junior high age will perform experiments, participate in engaging field trips, and develop techniques in traditional and non traditional dance forms. Planned experimental activities include: chicken dissection, microscope skill lessons, a bridge building competition, DNA extraction, a game modeling disease spread, and the creation of electromagnets. Several field trips are planned, such as a visit to a hydroelectric dam and a sustainable farm. One of our partners, MindLeaps, will bring lessons on traditional Guinean dance, hip-hop, and classical ballet. Instructors will praise effort and use growth mindset tools like summarizing to help students access long-term memory.  A "growth mindset" is a way of learning that is supported by research in neuroplasticity and psychology. It encourages critical thinking and failure, two aspects of learning that are never emphasized in the memorization-bound Guinean education system. We believe that by opening our students eyes to a "growth mindset" and engaging them fully through art and dance in addition to science, engineering, math and critical thinking skills, we can make a lasting impact on the leaders of today and tomorrow.We Need Your Support... How You Can HelpWe need to raise $27,541 to successfully run, evaluate and begin expanding this program so that it has a long term impact that not only works to give the students the tools to empower themselves but also tools for teachers in country to help sustain and incorporate growth mindset within Guinea's educational system. Small changes can have a big impact and your support makes the difference in how big that impact is.The funds raised will cover the following expenses:
Materials required to teach the curriculum and for participants to design and build projects and experiments
Materials  and curriculum for local instructors to take back to their schools after the camp to create after-school science clubs;
Create 5 year around after-school STEAM clubs at 5 different schools;
Food and snacks for the participants
Round trip flights to/from Guinea for our instructors;
Internet usage during the camp- Technology aspect of Camp
Pre- and post-camp assessment and evaluations for all camp participants.
Modest stipends for our volunteer staff
Lodging and transportation for international instructors;
Advertising and branding
'Contribute to Sustainable Hope'One very successful event that members of our team led was a National Science Camp. We’re using the framework from that, combined with current learning methods and artistic outlets to make a significant change in the lives of the 50 students and 5 teachers at our camps. We know from previous camps that students introduced to new, exciting experiences will go home with confidence and a new found curiosity in exploring STEAM and its correlation to the challenges that their communities face. Additionally, we will be training 5 Guinean teachers from across the country on how to run camps like this one in their own schools. Not only will they participate in our camp, but they’ll go home with a written guide and materials that they would never have been able to procure otherwise, like microscopes, calculators, and test tubes. Once our camp is finished at the end of July, we will encourage the teachers to organize their own camps, ideally right before school starts in October and create after-school science clubs. If each of our five teachers holds a camp with 30 students per semester, our project will have been responsible for bringing scientific discovery to 300 students in one year. We are currently in the process of creating a tool to assess the camp and the impact that our 5 teachers will have. We are committed to giving hope to Guinea's future STEAM leaders and hope you join us in our initiative.
